docs.text: gregg araki's the doom generation was possibly the very worst film ever made .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: so why did i see his latest teen bisexual angst opus ?
docs.label: negative

docs.text: first of all , some of the reviews were fairly positive .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: also , the cast , consisting of cameos from dozens of washed up ex tv stars ( including christopher knight , eve plumb , shannen doherty , and david leisure ) was promising .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: last of all , i wanted to give arraki one more chance .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: i mean , the guy can't be that untalented , can he ?
docs.label: negative

docs.text: the answer to that question is three letters long .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: nowhere follows the character dark on his wild and odd journey through los angeles .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: since arraki doesn't know how to make anything coherent , it's hard to describe the plot .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: let's just say that dark spends the bulk of the movie whining that his girlfriend won't make a commitment to him and jealous because she sleeps around with other guys and girls .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: the only remotely compelling storyline involves sarah lassez as a teen who has a chance encounter with a famous tv star .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: he turns out to be a nice guy who doesn't care for fame and wishes he could walk down the street without being mobbed by fans .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: this story has a shocking twist and a tragic end that i did not see coming .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: it is the first time i ever felt any compassion for a character created by arraki , and this can be attributed to the appealing performance of lassez .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: i thought maybe arraki was improving in his craft .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: he works better with the camera this time around , especially in the early scenes .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: halfway through the film , i didn't necessarily find myself enjoying the film , but it seemed like a considerable improvement on the doom generation .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: then as the movie went on , arraki loses all sensibility and introduces us to exploding heads , twisted sex games , and alien abductions .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: it's sad , because he almost actually had some decent material here , but he ruined it with his usual in your face " i'm such a renegade maverick filmmaker , look what i can do " attitude .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: the performances are generally better than in the doom generation , which isn't saying much .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: at least we don't have to suffer jonathan " i am the most hideous man in america " schaech .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: we are , however treated to another round of james " i'm more wooden than keanu " duval .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: sarah lassez gives the best performance in the film , and kathleen robertson ( formerly of 90210 and now arraki's wife ) and rachel true are talented actresses caught up in this mess .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: of the tv star cameos , john ritter is the most interesting as a deranged right wing tv evangelist .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: if i prefer nowhere to the doom generation , it is only in the way that i would prefer being assassinated than receive constant physical torture .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: maybe greg arraki doesn't want you to like his characters .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: maybe he wants to laugh and make fun of those of us who try to care about them .
docs.label: negative

docs.text: maybe he just wanted to piss me off .
